        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> I agree that modeline itself is not too interesting, but continuing to develop it and build scar-tissue around it is even less interesting.\n\n100% agree that vim's `'modelinestrict'` is not the way to go. However...\n\n> Instead we should leverage the trust mechanism for all kinds of \\\"environment-specific auto-execution\\\", of which modeline is one such case.\n\nUnlike exrc, modelines can only set certain options, and do not execute arbitrary code. If an option is unsafe to set, support for it should be removed from the modeline entirely. Otherwise, for options like `'filetype'`, which indirectly run (non-arbitrary) code, the issue is not with the modeline, but instead with the need to harden ftplugins. An attacker doesn't necessarily need to use a modeline to get Nvim to set a certain filetype.\n\nIf modelines are just fundamentally insecure for a reason that I'm unaware of (the ftplugin situation being hopeless, other modeline options being fundamentally insecure, large attack area, etc.) then I do fully support using `:trust` to handle modelines, as it is the next best solution. Just hoping that we can avoid needing to do so :)",
